Note on all masks
widgets_values:
All of this is to make a more refined very fainted "aura" outline blur mask on the character so the normal inpaint performs better and avoid superposition on denoise. 

Might be completely unecessery for inpainting control-net but I already had this done for another workflow, so why not.

YOu can tinker with the blue nodes values here

nodes.title: Note on all masks
widgets_values:
IMPORTANT!!
If you are going to inpaint the WHOLE image just leaving a small area intact, lets say, leave the face only and change the whole background, plase don't use this GREEN group, because the "Aura" will affect the face. Bypass it on the CONTROL ROOM

nodes.title: How visible should the "aura" around the mask be? More is MORE visible

widgets_values:
Please input YOUR loras here â†’â†’â†’â†’â†’


its optional. You can add as many as you want or just leave it at 0.

THIS NODE IS FOR USE WHEN using Localized Inpaiting:

Load the same image here (needs to be the same size) and make a SECOND mask here. It should be the area you want to have as context.

This will make the inpainting not use the full image but the "inpainted area" + "this context mask" as the image area. This can save you generation time if your whole image is too big. This will always inpint at 1024 max.

- right click > open mask editor

You can load a black and white previously saved mask (external mask) as well. If you do, change the ABOVE switch to true. This is NOT the inpainted area, but can include it if you want.

Example: I want to inpaint the eyes but have the whole face as context. Mask it on the above node and here you mask the whole face.
